name: m33
text1: "NASA's Hubble Space Telescope has produced its largest mosaic image ever of the Triangulum galaxy (M33). This image spans 14
text3: Triangulum seems to have emerged from the ages having interacted little with other galaxies, maintaining a neat, organized spiral and plenty of material for churning out new stars.
column8: Astronomers will investigate the impact of Triangulum's high star formation rate density as they comb through the huge trove of data gathered by Hubble. These contradictory features — a quiet past coupled to vigorous star formation — make Triangulum a fascinating member of the Local Group, providing key comparisons and contrasts with the Milky Way and our most massive neighbor, Andromeda.

name: horse head nebula
text1: "Hubble Sees a Horsehead of a Different Color"
text2: "Backlit wisps along the Horsehead Nebula upper ridge are being illuminated by Sigma Orionis
text3: a young five-star system just off the top of this image from the Hubble Space Telescope"

name: m51
text1: "NASA released new views today of two of the most well-known objects Hubble has ever observed: the Whirlpool Galaxy (spiral galaxy M51) [left] and the Eagle Nebula [right]. "
text2: "These new images are among the largest and sharpest Hubble has ever taken."
text3: "They were made with Hubble's newest camera
column8: the Advanced Camera for Surveys (ACS). The images are so incredibly sharp
column9: they could be enlarged to billboard size and still retain stunning details."
